<br>
As for the 'what makes a legitimate FCFS', I would think it depends on the guild and the mob, really, which makes this question a problem. I would think that a combination of a time limit and asking the guild 'up' for the mob about their ready status would work; that would put the duty on the guild interested in the FCFS nature of the mob, but getting permission earlier than, say, (1/2/3) hours before the patch would count as a pass, maybe? Or at least that a guild would not be allowed to mobilize on a mob under the pretense of FCFS until 3 hours before, and only after the guild up has said &quot;yeah, we're not gunna take it before the patch&quot; so as to eliminate rotation guilds racing for a mob. <br>
<br>
Though I suspect that would lead to like, 10 tells a night to various guilds on the day before a patch... <br>
<br>
Make a hotkey that says &quot;NO KITTY THAT'S MY POT PIE&quot; I guess... <br>
<br>
Sorry, I digress. <br>
<br>
Another idea would be a system by which guilds who know a mob is going to be patch eaten that they are up for, would be to send tells to other guilds on the rotation asking if they want it, sort of a &quot;giving&quot; of the mob to another, so the attempt wouldnt' actually turn into a FCFS race between guilds already on the rotation. <br>
<br>
Third option would be to post the release of the mob to the RTA at a time period before the patch, so that the mob could go FCFS for all, and then be won by whomever can get to it. <br>
<br>
Or maybe just have all mobs go FCFS a set time before a patch... <br>
<br>
Discussion would work on this, yep. <br>
<br>
